observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:

a.	Conduct reassessment and revision of the local revenue code particularly on the MEEDO Code of the Municipality;

b.	Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to enforce collection of the delinquent rentals and adhere to the timing of collection as prescribed by Section 5G.02 of the 2017 Revised Municipal Revenue Code of Sapang Dalaga, Misamis Occidental;

c.	Execute contract complete with details addressing the multiple deficiencies noted as regards approval of the Municipality of the lease, rental rate, term of contract and timing of rental payments; and

d.	Execute a lease contract for the five (5) stalls being rented out with no lease contract following the 5B.1 and 5B.2 - Rentals of Personal and Real Properties Owned by the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct a thorough reconciliation of the variance of ₱16,175,459.35 between the GL and the SL; Henceforth, ensure all cash advances are accounted for and discrepancies are resolved;
Investigate and address the negative balances of ₱2,364,708.61 in the schedules and ensure that the corrections are backed by proper documentation and audit trail;
Require the service provider of the accounting system to create Subsidiary Ledger for every entry in the General Ledger; and
Conduct monthly or quarterly reviews of cash advances to ensure timely detection and resolution of discrepancies.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to identify the monetary value of the remaining drugs and medicines inventory at year-end and make the necessary adjusting entries, taking into account the proper account to be debited for the year-end balance;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate to prepare and maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively not only for Drugs and Medicines for Distribution account;
Require the Inventory Committee of the municipality to conduct a physical count of the donated drugs and medicines, and to perform an appraisal of their value. This appraisal shall serve as the basis of the accounting personnel in recording;
Direct all Department Head to promptly inform the Accounting Office and the General Services Office (GSO) of all future donations to ensure proper accounting and monitoring.; and
Instruct the Municipal Health Officer to implement proper inventory monitoring and strengthen accountability mechanisms by ensuring that the distribution logbook is consistently maintained and utilized as a reference. Additionally, direct the Municipal Health Officer to regularly furnish the Municipal Accountant and the GSO- Designate with a copy of the monthly inventory report to ensure accurate and timely recording in the books of accounts.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the GSO - Designate and Municipal Accountant - for current purchases onwards-to religiously prepare and maintain the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, and reconcile both records regularly pending completion of one-time cleansing;
Instruct the GSO - Designate to issue PAR to end users for all issuances of property and equipment;
Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification, and
Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count and to prepare report on the physical count in order to monitor existence of the said properties, not to mention their physical condition.

We recommended that the management:

a.	Demand immediate settlement or liquidation of cash advances and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement is made after sending three demand letters;

b.	Cease from granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made; 

c.	Stop the practice of granting cash advances to elective officials for purposes other than that of traveling expenses; and 

d.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to reconcile records in order to adjust negative SLs.

We recommended that management:

a.	Direct the Municipal Engineer to make the Certificates of Completion for the projects Concreting of Macabibo Road leading to Macabibo Elementary. School and Concreting of Shoulder paved along Farm to Market Road Caluya with Drainage.

b.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary correcting entries to recognize completed projects as of December 31, 2023 and subsequently recognize corresponding depreciation expense;

c.	Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to: - for current purchases onwards-to religiously prepare and maintain the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, and reconcile both records regularly and conduct physical count, pending completion of one-time cleansing;

d.	Instruct the GSO to issue PAR to end users for all issuances of property and equipment; and

e.	Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification.

We recommended that management:

a.	Direct the BAC Secretariat to strictly adhere to the prescribed period for submission of contracts as provided for in COA Circular No. 2009-001; 

b.	Direct the BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents needed for the technical review by the Technical Audit Specialist; 

c.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to religiously comply with the proper accounting prescribed by the NGAS Manual using the Revised Chart of Accounts, 

d.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to record in the Road Networks account the seven completed ELCAC Programs; and

e.	Prepare the quarterly reports on fund utilization and status of program/project implementation.

