We recommended that management require the Accounting Office to record first the purchases of drugs, medicines, and other supplies and materials under inventory account and maintain supplies ledger cards;

Enjoin the General Service Office or the Municipal Treasurer as the case maybe to prepare and maintain stock cards which should always be reconciled with the ledger cards of the accounting; and
Require the RHU inventory in-charge to submit utilization report to the Municipal Treasury for them to prepare and submit SSMI as basis of the Accounting Office in crediting or deducting inventory accounts and recognizing the expense accounts.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and Treasury Unit (in the absence of a separate Supply Unit) and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
Provide additional manpower at the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to aide the Municipal Treasurer in the supply and property management of the LGU;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

We have recommended that management:

Instruct the municipal accountant to prioritize locating the files which are the basis for BRS preparation;

Study the necessity and length of service to hire additional personnel to address the backlog;

Direct the municipal treasurer to transmit on time the disbursement vouchers and official receipts; and

Require the municipal treasurer to obtain a copy of screenshot of bank transactions as initial basis for the accountant and hasten the preparation of BRS.

We have recommended to management to direct the Municipal Treasurer to post the Notice of Delinquency in the Payment of Real Property Tax and other taxes in a publicly accessible and conspicuous place in each barangay of the municipal government;

Avail of the civil remedies provided for in Chapter IV, Title I, Book II of R.A. 7160 and develop other feasible strategies to enhance collections of delinquent taxes from taxpayers; and

Conduct periodic reconciliation of Real Property Tax Receivable with the Accountant and Assessor and to establish database for each individual Real Property Taxpayers.

We have recommended that management direct the Collectors to remit intact all collections at the end of each business day to prevent any liability arising from possible losses resulting from unlawful use or application thereof, and for all losses attributable to negligence in keeping of the funds; 

Require the Collectors to prepare and submit the monthly RAAF to report the receipts and issuances of accountable forms and the outstanding balance under his/her custody; and

Require the Liquidating Officer and Municipal Treasurer to monitor the collectors’ compliance of the required daily remittance of collections and to report any non-compliance to the Agency Head for proper action.

